@flexiarg writing-coherence/throat-clearing-close
@title End on the Claim, Not the Attitude
@keywords closing, paragraph, claim, attitude, softener, exec-summary, throat-clearing
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/hedged-lift writing-coherence/scope-mush]

! conclusion: A paragraph — especially an executive-summary or section-closing paragraph — earns its ending by leaving the reader with a claim.  When the last sentence instead expresses an aim, hope, or authorial posture toward the work, it tells the reader what the writer feels rather than what they argue, and the paragraph loses its structural payload.
  + context: AI-assisted prose tends to close warm: "the overall aim is to help X inhabit this space", "we hope this will serve as a starting point", "this paper aims to contribute to...".  These closers function as rhetorical exhale after the real argument.  They are not wrong — they are under-committed.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: warmth / attitude ↔ claim / proposition.
    Real: warmth signals intellectual humility and softens the ask; a claim commits, which is riskier and harder to retract.  Both have costs.
    Irreducible: a single sentence cannot be simultaneously maximally warm and maximally propositional; the two pull in opposite directions.
    Active: the pull recurs at every paragraph close — warmth wants the last word because it is easier to write.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Commit: replace the softener with the strongest claim the paragraph supports.  "This paper argues X" lands harder than "this paper aims to help with X".
    (2) Relocate warmth: move the attitudinal sentence upstream (into the paragraph's opening or the section intro) so it frames rather than closes, and end on the claim.
    (3) Cut: delete the softener entirely.  Readers rarely miss it; they were already weighing the claim.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the last sentence of the paragraph states a proposition a careful reader could disagree with.  Failing when: the last sentence expresses an aim, a hope, a promise of help, or a meta-reflection about what the paper is doing.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Aim-as-close: "the aim is to help X inhabit / learn / grow / develop".
    - Hope-as-close: "we hope this contributes to / opens a conversation about".
    - Meta-as-close: "this paper attempts to set out a framework for...".
    - Self-congratulation: "this approach represents a promising direction".
